WHAT IS THIS FILE
The certified standard reference for T/SUCA 053-2026, the world's first
technical specification for photoluminescent quantum dot Mini/MicroLED
display terminals. It defines the optical performance parameters, colour
gamut, luminance, and reliability requirements for QD-enhanced MicroLED
displays.

WHY IT EXISTS
Quantum dot Mini/MicroLED displays represent the convergence of two
transformative technologies. Without a standard, manufacturers and
content creators lack a common language for performance. This standard,
published in March 2026 by the Shenzhen 8K UHD Video Industry
Cooperation Alliance, fills a global gap. GIOP integrates it as the
reference display model for next-generation emissive displays.

HOW IT WORKS
1. Technology Principle:
   Photoluminescent quantum dots (QDs) absorb blue MicroLED emission
   (~450 nm) and re-emit at red (~630 nm) and green (~530 nm). The QD
   layer is integrated directly with the MicroLED array (in-situ
   integration).

2. Color Gamut Requirements:
   DCI-P3 coverage: ≥ 99%
   BT.2020 coverage: ≥ 90%
   White point: D65 (tolerance Δu'v' < 0.003)

3. Luminance:
   Peak luminance: ≥ 1000 cd/m² (HDR)
   Full-screen sustained: ≥ 500 cd/m²
   Black level: ≤ 0.0005 cd/m²

4. Photoluminescence Efficiency:
   η_PL = photons_emitted / photons_absorbed ≥ 0.85
   QD lifetime: L70 > 30,000 hours at 50°C.

5. Measurement Methods:
   Luminance and colour measured using a spectroradiometer at 25°C.
   Angular colour shift Δu'v' < 0.005 at ±60° viewing angle.

WHERE IT IS DEPLOYED
- Next-generation consumer TVs and professional mastering monitors
- Virtual production LED walls
- AR/VR microdisplays
- GIOP HDR mastering displays.

WHO USES IT
Display manufacturers; L2 Engineers building ODTs for QD-MicroLED
displays; L3 Colorists mastering for premium emissive displays.

WHAT PROBLEM IT SOLVES
Establishes the first globally recognised quality benchmark for QD-
MicroLED displays. Enables GIOP to define ODTs that exploit the full
colour volume and luminance of this emerging display technology.

